<br>
The reduced costs for shouts will probably help quite a lot, and is a good start.<br>
<br>
The song of rest is now officialy not useless anymore. It's nice that they finally &quot;fixed&quot; it, but the thing that I don't like is that it was only the bare minimal thing they could do to make the song viable. Bye bye all dreams like a pow or end regen component.<br>
It is now a decent downtime reducer in solo PvE, nothing less, nothing more. It removes one item from the &quot;to fix&quot; list but I don't think it will be of much help to the class balance in general, esp RvR.<br>
<br>
Basically, here's my take. I am still seriously jealous/pissed off/envious/whateveryoucallit about the minstrel love. Not because they didn't deserve some lovin', but because it makes the question about what friggin' ROLE the skald is supposed to fulfill in the grand scheme of things even more acute than before, when we had a &quot;borther-in-gimpiness&quot; (kinda, I am exaggerating a bit, but you see my point here).<br>
<br>
The three music classes do all have the speed song, which is the core ability of the classes. Ok. So put this out of the equation.<br>
Oh and yes, I will certainly hear criticism about those comparisons : &quot;Kjeld, Minstrels, Bards and Minstrels are wholly different classes, you'd better compare skalds to champion or thane, etc ...&quot;<br>
My answer is no. It is crystal clear that we are not considered as &quot; (melee) hybrids&quot;, and it is prety much evident since the &quot;caster balance&quot; patch and the &quot;melee rebalancing patch&quot; (don't remember the numbers, the caster patch was the one which reworked many caster spell lines and introduced resistances), where skalds were purposedly and blatantly left out from hybrid rebalancing and discussions. Everytime some skald raises a concern about class balance, the inevitable answer is &quot;but you have speed (tm)&quot; and &quot;you should not expect to beat a tank/light fighter/hybrid/assassin, like a bard or minstrel&quot;.<br>
So we have been pigeonhold by both devs and the player base in the &quot;speed class that should never expect to fight like an hybrid&quot;, so, in the end, my comparison is valid <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  We should directly compare our abilities to minstrel's and bard's (even if it is to admit we fight significantly better <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
Wow, that was a long winded digression. Let's get back on tracks.<br>
<br>
So you have the bard, which, despite some issues, is a strong and versatile support class, with PRIMARY crowd control, secondary healing/buffing (-&gt; all of this = role), AND strong support songs (end, pow).<br>
<br>
Then, the minstrel, after this patch, has become a canny scoundrel that can sneak up behind enmy lines and unleash some nasty &quot;behind castle walls&quot; stuns and mezzes (-&gt; role), AND still received very strong support that rivals, if not exceed bard's support (anti mez, turnblade, end). Not to mention the SoS wildcard.<br>
<br>
So we now have two strongly defined classes, with a distinct and fully fleshed-out role PLUS awesome support skills.<br>
<br>
And the skald ? Our role is that of the melee music class, yet the subject of skald melee has been pretty much beaten to death ... we do not perform as well in our melee role as minstrels and bards perform in their respective role.<br>
<br>
Then, on top of that role, minstrels and bards have awesome support, while skalds still rely entirely upon a flawed, bugged, and lacking damage add song.<br>
<br>
Well, my analysis is surely debatable and subjective, but at this time, I almost feel that to be put up to par, skalds should receive *both* improvements  to their staying power in melee *and* some loving to their support abilities.<br>
I can certainly imagine how hard it will be to reach this balance ... but an significant advance in either of those areas are imho needed without a single doubt. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c2a2><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mistarbdj>Mistar BDJ</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Participant</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#ff0000>(2/18/03 9:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=509.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Well</span><hr size=1> stealing this from sideshow~...sorry bud<br>
-edited to make it an ra<br>
<br>
Shout Of Reflection.<br>
This is a shout spell that affects all group members in a 2000 unit radius.  It acts like a buff so when its shouted you recieve the &quot;reflective buff&quot;, It lasts 1 minute and is on a 30 minute timer.  It costs 14 Realm Ability points.  It reflects both melee and magic damage back at the enemy who hit/cast you. The amount of damage reflected is based on 50% x resist of the party member that is hit. I'll use heat damage for example here...<br>
<br>
Lets say player x has a 25% resist to fire. When a 200 dmg fire spell hits him, it removes 25% or 50 dmg and he actually gets hit for 150 (-50). If that same player has the Shout Of Reflection &quot;buff&quot; on him then 50% of that 50 damage he resisted is targetted back at the caster.  In essence 25 damage gets reflected.<br>
<br>
Name: Shout of Reflection<br>
Cost: 14 Realm Ability Points<br>
Description: 50% Of Resisted Damage Is Reflected<br>
Effect: Group<br>
Range: 2000<br>
Cast: Instant<br>
Duration: 1 minute<br>
Refresh Timer: 30 minutes<br>
<br>
Effects such as mez/stun/disease/debuffs would not be effected by the shout.<br>
<br>
Also a 100 point weaponskill boost is needed for skalds.  This would put us under light tanks but above assassins/snipers and at an equal level with other tank hybrids.  Thanes and Champions have a str/con buff to supplenment their weaponskill/hitpoints.  Skalds can use a weaponskill boost since it will increase their damage output puting them closer to appropriate damage output for a viking base class and making it so that putting points into their defensive ability, parry, would be more effective.  This would allow skald to fulfill their role of a subpar tank with group friendly speed since they are dealing more damage but they are not recieving more hitpoints and are still below light tanks/main tanks for hitpoints but can make better use of their offensive abilites and defensive abilities due to increased weaponskill. <p>Kaldazar Vec 50th Level Norse Skald<br>
Cameela NoVecNoBuffs 48th Level Norse Healer<br>
